Resident dumb fox poster back with some more insight on foxes.

Foxes are apparently very skittish and shy, even the social ones. Like you’ll need to be a bit careful around them or they’ll dart in the other direction. That specific trait really only applies to the extremely shy ones, but even the social foxes still jump at unexpected touches.

I think it’s been established here that foxes don’t really bark or howl like other canines. They can, but they opt for screaming and gekkering instead. And also when their ears fold back and they make a :V face, they’re being threatening, or at least their best attempt at it.

Aside from marshmallows and raw meat, some foxes will fall in love with some weird and random foods. Like cucumbers or green beans. Arctics also require the most protein in their diet.

Female arctics are also, on average, only slightly lighter in weight than males, but males have a significantly wider range of weight they could potentially be.

Foxes will also sit on things they want to mark as theirs, whether it’s an object or a person, due to a scent gland present on the underside of their tails. The gland is also present on other canines, but I’m not sure if they use it like foxes.

There are many different color morphs for red foxes, and I believe the rarest is the pink champagne fox. Their fur is tinged to look slightly pink, hence the name. I believe there have been only two recorded foxes with that color morph, but there could have been more in the years following the article I read on it. Like most morphs, it is achieved through selective breeding.

Also semi-related but do you know Finnegan? The fox that’s probably the second/third most popular on the internet? He apparently only acts the way he does in the videos around his owner. Around most other people, he has a bit of a resting bitch face, and will only come to you for treats. I think his owner specified that he looks like he’s “mean muggin’” you for treats.

Phi here, I won't give a time frame on the next CotW update but I did notice something funny when I was rereading and working on it earlier today.

I was playing the Watchman movie in the background and realized I stole a line from the film. On line 1333 Dr. Hopper says to Jake "Without condoning or condemning; I understand why..."

That's the same line Dr. Manhattan gives to Adrian Veidt after he buys into Veidt's plan. The thing is I hadn't seen the movie since it came out in 2009 and hadn't read the comic since before that. So I was both impressed that I remembered the line verbatim and disappointed with myself that I ripped it off. It was a weird moment and derailed my revisions.

Usually when I feel weird about a line I'll remember where it actually came from or rewrite it to find something that doesn't feel weird. But this one was odd because it seemed perfect and I was really proud of it only to realize it wasn't mine much later. I wrote that months ago and didn't notice or give it a second thought. So I've been kind of paranoid with my rereading this evening.

It weirded me out and now I have to change the line. It's a trivial change, but I find the whole thing very odd and thought it was worth sharing with the thread. I'm wondering if any other writers were really proud of something like a turn of phrase or a metaphor only to realize much later that their subconscious stole it from somewhere else?

There's a funny story about that. Japan back then got the early editions of D&D translated which was when orcs were very pig-like and kobolds were weird little dog people. But they didn't get the newer editions translated which changed orcs to big green humans with tusks, reptile kobolds, etc. And since all the Jap media made around western style fantasy settings take heavily from D&D you see a lot of the those old designs for stuff like orcs and kobolds. And they were used enough in popular games, manga, anime, etc it's now stuck with how those creatures look.
